Cheung Kong, Hutchison, Rio, Security Bank: Asia Ex-Japan Equities Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-08-04T21:50:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-04/cheung-kong-hutchison-rio-tinto-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding Japan.
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Advanced Info Service Pcl (ADVANC)  : Thailand’s biggest
mobile phone company reported net income in the second quarter
climbed 26 percent to 6.12 billion baht ($205 million). The
shares added 0.4 percent to 119.5 baht.  Chimei Innolux Corp. (3481)  (3481 TT): Taiwan’s largest maker of
liquid-crystal displays posted its fourth consecutive loss as
sales of TVs slow and global economic uncertainty weighs down
demand. Second-quarter net loss was NT$13 billion ($450 million),
compared with a NT$9.5 billion profit a year earlier, the Miaoli,
Taiwan-based company said in a statement. The average of 13
analysts’ estimates compiled by Bloomberg was for a loss of
NT$6.47 billion. Chimei dropped 4.1 percent to NT$15.05.  Cheung Kong (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK): The Hong Kong developer
controlled by billionaire Li Ka-shing said first-half profit
almost tripled to HK$33.3 billion ($4.27 billion), or HK$14.36 a
share, from a restated HK$12.3 billion, or HK$5.33 a share, a
year earlier. That missed the median HK$34.9 billion estimate of
five analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News.  Cheung Kong  fell 0.08
percent to HK$119.60.  Guinness Anchor Bhd. (GUIN)  : Malaysia’s biggest brewer
by market value said profit in the fourth quarter ended June 30
fell 18 percent from a year earlier to 29.1 million ringgit,
according to an exchange filing. The shares rose 1.5 percent to
10.86 ringgit.  Hutchison Whampoa Ltd. (13)  (13 HK): Hong Kong billionaire Li
Ka-shing’s biggest company reported first-half profit increased
to HK$46.3 billion ($5.9 billion), or HK$10.86 a share, from
HK$6.3 billion, or HK$1.48, a year earlier, the Hong Kong-based
company said in a statement. This missed the HK$51 billion
median of five analysts’ estimates in a Bloomberg News survey.
Hutchison declined 0.9 percent to HK$90.35.  Metro Pacific Investments Corp. (MPI)  : The Philippine
unit of Hong Kong’s First Pacific Co.’s first-half reported net
income increased 12 percent to 1.96 billion pesos ($46 million),
the company said in an e-mailed statement. The stock declined
0.3 percent to 3.56 pesos.  Rio Tinto  Group (RIO AU): The second-largest mining company
reported first-half profit that missed analyst estimates as
costs and currency gains in Australia and Canada hurt earnings.
Underlying profit rose 35 percent to $7.8 billion, below the
$8.3 billion mean estimate of nine analysts compiled by
Bloomberg. Net income climbed 30 percent to $7.6 billion in the
six months ended June 30, from $5.8 billion a year earlier. Rio
expanded its share buyback by $2 billion to $7 billion. The
stock fell 1.3 percent to A$76.58.  Security Bank Corp. (SECB)  : The Manila-based lender’s
first-half net income increased 33 percent to 2.4 billion pesos
($57 million), a stock-exchange filing showed. The stock rose
4.4 percent to 97 pesos.  SM Investments Corp. (SM)  : The holding company of
Philippine billionaire  Henry Sy  expects to meet its 12 percent
to 14 percent profit growth target this year, Chief Financial
Officer Jose Sio said. The stock fell 1.1 percent to 534 pesos.  SM Prime Holdings Inc. (SMPH)  : The largest Philippine
shopping mall operator will continue with its expansion plans,
including accelerating the addition of malls in  China , even
without the sale of real-estate investment trusts, Chief
Financial Officer Jeffrey Lim said. The stock sank 1 percent to
11.52 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
 anguyen@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net . 